04944nam a22007095i 9780271093116DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710931167 a10.1515/97802710931162doi  a(DE-B1597)626893  a(OCoLC)1309956446  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0040002bisacsh1 aMurray, Billie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCombating Hate :bA Framework for Direct Action /cBillie Murray. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (196 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRhetoric and Democratic Deliberation ;v2800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Context Theory and the Counterspeech System -- t2 More-Speech Tactics -- t3 Combative Tactics -- t4 Allied Tactics -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe United States has a hate problem. In recent years, hate speech has led not only to deep division in our politics but also to violence, murder, and even insurrection. And yet established constitutional jurisprudence holds that all speech is protected as “content neutral” and that the proper democratic response to hateful expression is not regulation but “more speech.” So how can ordinary citizens stand up to hate groups when the state will not?In Combating Hate, Billie Murray proposes an answer to this question. As a participant in anti-racist and anti-fascist protests, including demonstrations against the Ku Klux Klan, neo-Nazis, and the Westboro Baptist Church, Murray witnessed firsthand the limitations of the “more speech” approach as well as the combative tactics of anti-fascist activists. She argues that this latter group, commonly known as antifa, embodies a radically different strategy for combating hate, one that explodes the myth of content neutrality and reveals hate speech to be a tactic of fascist organizing with very real, highly anti-democratic consequences. Drawing on communication theory and this on-the-ground experience, Murray presents a new strategy, which she calls “allied tactics,” rooted in the commitment to affirm, support, and even protect those who are the victims of hate speech.Engaging and sophisticated, Combating Hate contends that there are concrete ways to fight hate speech from the front lines. Murray’s urgent argument that we reconsider how to confront and fight this blight on American life is essential reading for the current era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeliberative democracy. 0aHate speech. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh  aAccount of counterspeech protests.  aHate speech.  aRhetorical analysis of anti-hate group protest.  aVision for moving beyond counterspeech protest.  aanti-fascism.  acounterspeech.  afree speech.  amore speech.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107669290 cprintz978027109279940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271093116?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271093116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271093116/original  a978-3-11-076692-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-P